---
import DocsLayout from '../../../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import Callout from '../../../../components/Callout.astro';
import Checklist from '../../../../components/Checklist.astro';
---

<DocsLayout title="Project 3: The interactive app" description="Create your own PRD, design spec, and architecture — then build a full-stack app from them.">
  <h1 class="mb-2">Project 3: The Interactive App</h1>
  <p class="text-xl text-primary font-medium mb-6">"I can turn a client brief into a PRD, design spec, and architecture — and build from it."</p>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">What you'll build</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Clay & Co — a pottery studio class booking system. Class listings with dates, times, and spots remaining. A signup form with client-side and server-side validation. Email confirmations for signups. Admin notifications when someone books a spot. Full-stack app building on the P2 tech stack: React frontend, FastAPI backend, PostgreSQL, Docker.</p>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">What's new (the +1)</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">For the first time, you create the planning artifacts yourself. The PRD, design spec, and architecture are no longer handed to you. You get a client brief and the tools to produce them: prompts to paste into an LLM, templates to structure the output, and review guidance to check what AI generates. Planning judgment becomes the skill.</p>

  <Callout variant="info">
    <p class="text-sm"><strong>Why this matters:</strong> Anyone can direct AI to implement a given spec. The harder skill is deciding what the spec should say. In Projects 1 and 2, you practised directing and verifying. Now you practise the judgment that comes before implementation — scoping, excluding, and structuring requirements so they can be built and verified.</p>
  </Callout>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">What success looks like</h2>
  <Checklist items={[
    "A working app where users can browse classes, sign up, and get confirmation emails",
    "A PRD you wrote that captured the right scope — no more, no less",
    "A design spec that reflects the client's preferences, not AI's defaults",
    "Architecture decisions you can defend — why this database schema, why this API structure",
    "A backlog you created and executed, not one that was handed to you",
  ]} />

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">What you'll learn</h2>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-text-secondary space-y-2 text-sm mb-8">
    <li>Write a PRD from a client conversation</li>
    <li>Create a design spec using AI + client input</li>
    <li>Make architecture decisions (not just review them)</li>
    <li>Create your own ticket backlog</li>
    <li>Set up a kanban board with GitHub Projects</li>
    <li>Configure ESLint and Prettier for code quality</li>
    <li>Handle form validation — client-side and server-side</li>
    <li>Integrate email sending (SendGrid, Mailgun, or Resend)</li>
    <li>Track test coverage with pytest-cov</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">Prerequisites</h2>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-text-secondary space-y-2 text-sm mb-8">
    <li>Completed <a href="/web-dev/projects/2">Project 2</a> and <a href="/web-dev/checkpoints/after-p2">Checkpoint After Project 2</a></li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">Estimated time</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-8">1-2 weeks. More tickets than P2 because you're also creating the planning artifacts — PRD, design spec, architecture, and backlog — before implementation begins.</p>

  <div class="mt-8 p-6 bg-primary-bg rounded-lg border border-primary/20 text-center">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-2">Start with the requirements</h2>
    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Meet the client, understand the brief, then write the PRD yourself.</p>
    <a
      href="/web-dev/projects/3/requirements"
      class="inline-block bg-primary hover:bg-primary-dark text-white font-semibold py-3 px-6 rounded-md transition-colors min-h-[44px]"
    >
      Start with the requirements →
    </a>
  </div>
</DocsLayout>
